revision.text:
'''Berkeley Media Studies Group''' (BMSG) conducts research on the influence of [[mass media]] over public health and social issues. The BMSG works with community groups, journalists, and public health professionals to use "the power of the media" to advance healthy public policy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Mission|url=http://www.bmsg.org/about/our-mission|website=bmsg.org|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> BMSG's goal is to use their research to support media and policy efforts of public health advocates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Research|url=http://www.bmsg.org/about/research|website=bmsg.org|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> It was founded in 1993 in [[Berkeley, California]], by Lawrence Wallack, DrPH, then-professor of public health at the [[University of California at Berkeley]], and Lori Dorfman, DrPH. It is a project of the Public Health Institute of Oakland, California.<ref>{{cite web|title=Off Balance: Youth, Race & Crime in the News|url=http://www.theppsc.org/Archives/School.Violence/Off-Balance-Youth.Race&Crime.In.The.News.htm|website=theppsc.org|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Activists Push for Berkeley Soda Tax|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/activists-push-for-berkeley-soda-tax/Content?oid=3966157|website=eastbayexpress.com|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref>

